\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 	
\f1\b\fs28 Background\
\pard\pardeftab709\sl288\slmult1\sa140

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 For decades Greenpeace has hired photographers and editors to document our activism and the environmental impacts various companies and initiatives have on our planet.  We've created an extensive library of rights managed, professional images and videos spanning 5 decades and 5 continents.  Our National Regional Offices (NROs) hire local photographers to provide content for campaigns and individual actions, and  those photographers sign a licensing agreement that in effect splits the copyright of a photograph fifty-fifty between Greenpeace and the photographer.\
Our current licensing agreement was formulated in 2010. From 2008 to 2010 the Library Team struggled to create policy within that agreement that allowed for Creative Commons Licenses. Now, five years later, we wish to revisit the contracts and agreements with content creators, with stronger more compelling evidence of the need to provide open-source content to drive open campaigning.\
In order to achieve a more open, modern and sustainable policy, we believe we need a multi-pronged approach. We need a strategy that takes into account a highly diverse organization with a highly diverse group of stakeholders.\
\pard\pardeftab709\li720\fi-720\sb140\sa120
